[[Abraham Lincoln]], the 16th [[President of the United States]], was [[Assassination|assassinated]] by well-known stage actor [[John Wilkes Booth]] on April 14, 1865, while attending the play ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' at [[Ford's Theatre]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]
Shot in the head as he watched the play,<ref name="Abel">{{cite book|last1=Abel|first1=E. Lawrence|title=A Finger in Lincoln's Brain: What Modern Science Reveals about Lincoln, His Assassination, and Its Aftermath|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ax0UBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q&f=false|quote=Forensic evidence clearly indicates Booth could not have fired at point-blank range{{nbsp}}... At a distance of three or more feet, the gunshot would not leave any stippling or any other residues on the surface of Lincoln's head{{nbsp}}... Dr. Robert Stone, the Lincoln's' family physician, was explicit: "The hair or scalp (on Lincoln's head) was not in the least burn[t]."}}</ref> Lincoln died the following day at 7:22&nbsp;a.m., in the [[Petersen House]] opposite the theater.<ref name = "Heritage">{{cite journal|title=How Did Lincoln Die?|journal=American Heritage|date=February–March 1995|volume=46|issue=1|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/how-did-lincoln-die?page=show|author=Richard A. R. Fraser, MD}}</ref>  He was the first American president to be assassinated;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/today/apr14.html |title=Lincoln Shot at Ford's Theater}}</ref>  [[funeral and burial of Abraham Lincoln|his funeral and burial]] marked an extended period of national mourning.

Occurring near the end of the [[American Civil War]], the assassination was part of a larger conspiracy intended by Booth to revive the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] cause by eliminating the three most important officials of the [[United States government]].
Conspirators [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]] and [[David Herold]] were assigned to kill [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]], and [[George Atzerodt]] was tasked with killing [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Andrew Johnson]].
Beyond Lincoln's death the plot failed: Seward was only wounded and Johnson's would-be attacker lost his nerve. After a dramatic initial escape, Booth was killed at the climax of a 12-day manhunt. Powell, Herold, Atzerodt and [[Mary Surratt]] were later hanged for their roles in the conspiracy.

==Background==
===Abandoned plan to kidnap Lincoln===

[[File:Lincoln-Warren-1865-03-06.jpeg|thumb|upright=0.70|left|The last known high-quality image of Lincoln, taken on the White House balcony, March 6, 1865]]
[[File:John Wilkes Booth-portrait.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|[[John Wilkes Booth]]]]
[[File:Mary Surratt house - Brady-Handy.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|The Surratt house]]
[[File:LincolnJohn.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|left|Booth was present as Lincoln delivered [[Lincoln's second inaugural address|his second inaugural address]] a month before the assassination.]]

John Wilkes Booth, born in [[Maryland]] into [[Booth family|a family of prominent stage actors]], had by the time of the assassination become a famous actor and national celebrity in his own right.
He was also an outspoken [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] sympathizer; in late 1860 he was initiated in the pro-Confederate [[Knights of the Golden Circle]] in [[Baltimore]].<ref name=brewer>{{cite book|first1=Warren |last1=Getler |first2=Bob |last2=Brewer |title=Shadow of the Sentinel |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=2003 |ISBN=978-0-7432-1968-6 |url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Shadow-of-the-Sentinel/Warren-Getler/9781416591160}}</ref>{{rp|67}}

In March 1864, [[Ulysses S. Grant]], commander of the Union armies, suspended the exchange of [[prisoners of war]] with the [[Confederate Army]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/USACWexchange.htm |title=Prisoner exchange |publisher=Spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605232902/http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/USACWexchange.htm |archivedate=June 5, 2011 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> to increase pressure on the manpower-starved South. Booth conceived a plan to kidnap Lincoln in order to blackmail the North into resuming prisoner exchanges,{{r|kauffman|p=130–4}} and recruited [[Samuel Arnold (Lincoln conspirator)|Samuel Arnold]], [[George Atzerodt]], [[David Herold]], [[Michael O'Laughlen]], [[Lewis Powell (assassin)|Lewis Powell]] (also known as "Lewis Paine"), and [[John Surratt]] to help him. Surratt's mother, [[Mary Surratt]], left her tavern in [[Clinton, Maryland|Surrattsville, Maryland]], and moved to a house in [[Washington, D.C.]],<!--THE WAY THIS WAS WRITTEN MAKES IT SOUND LIKE SHE MOVED TO D.C. IN ORDER TO FURTHER THE CONSPIRACY -- IS THAT WHAT'S MEANT?--> where Booth became a frequent visitor.

While Booth and Lincoln were not personally acquainted, Lincoln had seen Booth at Ford's in 1863.{{r|steers|page=419}}<ref>{{cite web|title=5 facts you may not know about Lincoln's assassination|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/media/abraham-lincoln-assassination-5-facts-you-may-not-know/2/|website=CBSNews.com|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=March 1, 2017|quote=Just a few days before delivering the Gettysburg Address in 1863, Lincoln went to the theater to see a play called "The Marble Heart" – a translated French production in which Booth played the villain.}}</ref><ref name = "Bogar">{{cite book|last1=Bogar|first1=Thomas A.|title=American Presidents Attend the Theatre: The Playgoing Experiences of Each Chief Executive|date=2006|publisher=McFarland|pages=100, 375–376|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TLfwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA100#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> After the assassination, actor Frank Mordaunt wrote that Lincoln admired Booth, whom Lincoln had repeatedly invited (without success) to visit the White House.<ref name=hay>{{cite book|last1=Hay|first1=John|editor1-last=Burlingame|editor1-first=Michael|editor2-last=Ettlinger|editor2-first=John R. Turner|title=Inside Lincoln's White House: The Complete Civil War Diary of John Hay|date=1999|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BnOVqu-11QIC&pg=PA325#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>{{rp|325–326}} Booth attended Lincoln's [[Second inauguration of Abraham Lincoln|second inauguration]] on March 4, writing in his diary afterwards: "What an excellent chance I had, if I wished, to kill the President on Inauguration day!"{{r|kauffman|p=174,437n.41}}

On March 17, Booth and the other conspirators planned to abduct Lincoln as he returned from a play at Campbell Military Hospital.<!--parking these refs here for a little while https://whitney.echomaryland.net/2/5/13/ http://rogerjnorton.com/Lincoln72.html http://www.mrlincolnswhitehouse.org/washington/the-war-effort/war-effort-campbell-general-hospital/ https://books.google.com/books?id=mUzP2ziQte4C&pg=PA111&dq=Campbell+Hospital+Soldiers+Home&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiF_ca-wfjVAhWk4IMKHfIfDhIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Campbell%20Hospital%20Soldiers%20Home&f=false (One of 3 dozen military hospitals. Campbell was aka Campbell Military Hospital/Campbell General Hospital/Campbell Hospital)--> But Lincoln did not go to the play, instead attending a ceremony at the National Hotel;{{r|kauffman|p=185}} Booth was living at the National Hotel at the time and, had he not gone to the hospital for the abortive kidnap attempt, might have been able to attack Lincoln at the hotel.{{r|kauffman|p=185-6,439n17}}{{r|swanson|p=25}}

Meanwhile, the Confederacy was collapsing. On April 3, [[Richmond, Virginia]], the Confederate capital, fell to the Union Army. On April 9 the [[General-in-Chief of the Confederate States Army]] [[Robert E. Lee]] and his [[Army of Northern Virginia]]  [[Battle of Appomattox Court House#Surrender|surrendered]] to the [[Commanding General of the United States Army]] [[Ulysses S. Grant]] and his [[Army of the Potomac]] after the [[Battle of Appomattox Court House]].  Confederate President [[Jefferson Davis]] and other Confederate officials had fled. But Booth continued to believe in the Confederate cause and sought a way to salvage it.{{r|goodwin|p=728}}{{clear left}}

===Motive===
{{LincolnSeries}}
{{Further|John Wilkes Booth#Theories of Booth's motivation}}
There are various theories about Booth's motivations. In a letter to his mother, he wrote of his desire to avenge the South.<ref name=kauffman252>{{cite book|last1=Kauffman|first1=John W.|title=American Brutus: John Wilkes Booth and the Lincoln Conspiracies|date=December 18, 2007|publisher=[[Random House]]|page=252|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=86RH6NNCl0QC&pg=252#v=onepage&q&f=false|quote="...that I have not a single selfish motive to spur me on to this, nothing save the sacred duty, I feel I owe the cause I love, the cause of the South.}}</ref> Doris Kearns Goodwin has endorsed the idea that another factor was Booth’s rivalry with his well-known older brother, actor [[Edwin Booth]], who was a loyal Unionist.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goodwin|first1=Doris Kearns|title=My Thoughts Be Bloody: The Bitter Rivalry Between Edwin and John Wilkes Booth That Led to an American Tragedy (Foreword)|date=October 19, 2010|publisher=Simon & Schuster|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vBSQUOMDMLEC&pg=PR11#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> [[David S. Reynolds]] believes Booth greatly admired the abolitionist [[John Brown (abolitionist)|John Brown]];<ref name ="Reynolds">{{cite web|last1=Reynolds|first1=David S.|title=John Wilkes Booth and the Higher Law|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/04/john-wilkes-booth-and-the-higher-law/385461/|publisher=''[[The Atlantic]]''|date=April 12, 2015}}</ref> Booth’s sister [[Asia Booth Clarke]] quoted him as saying: "John Brown was a man inspired, the grandest character of the century!"{{r|Reynolds}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Clarke|first1=Asia Booth|title=The Unlocked Book: A Memoir of John Wilkes Booth by his Sister|date=1938|publisher=Faber & Faber|page=124}}</ref>
On April 11, Booth attended Lincoln's speech at the [[White House]] in which Lincoln promoted voting rights for blacks;<ref>{{cite web |title=Last Public Address |url=http://showcase.netins.net/web/creative/lincoln/speeches/last.htm |date=April 11, 1865 |accessdate=2008-09-15 |work=Speeches and Writings |publisher=Abraham Lincoln Online}}</ref> Booth said
"That means <!--DO NOT ALTER THIS EXACT QUOTE-->nigger<!--DO NOT ALTER THIS EXACT QUOTE--> citizenship{{nbsp}}... That is the last speech he will ever give." He urged [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]] to shoot Lincoln on the spot, and when Powell refused for fear of the crowd, said to David Herold, "By God, I'll put him through."<ref>{{cite book|last=Donald | first=David Herbert | title=Lincoln | location=New York | publisher=Touchstone | year=1995 | page=588}}</ref>{{r|steers|page=91}}

===Lincoln's premonitions===
According to [[Ward Hill Lamon]], three days before his death Lincoln related a dream in which he wandered the White House searching for the source of mournful sounds:

{{quote|I kept on until I arrived at the [[East Room]], which I entered. There I met with a sickening surprise. Before me was a [[catafalque]], on which rested a corpse wrapped in funeral vestments. Around it were stationed soldiers who were acting as guards; and there was a throng of people, gazing mournfully upon the corpse, whose face was covered, others weeping pitifully. "Who is dead in the White House?" I demanded of one of the soldiers, "The President," was his answer; "he was killed by an assassin."<ref>p.&nbsp;116–117 of Recollections of Abraham Lincoln 1847–1865 by Ward Hill Lamon (Lincoln, University of Nebraska Press, 1999).</ref>}}

For months Lincoln had looked pale and haggard, but on the morning of the assassination he told people how happy he was. First Lady [[Mary Todd Lincoln]] felt such talk could bring bad luck.{{r|kunhardtlincoln|p=346}} Lincoln told his cabinet that he had dreamed of being on a "singular and indescribable vessel that was moving with great rapidity toward a dark and indefinite shore", and that he'd had the same dream before "nearly every great and important event of the War" such as the victories at [[Antietam]], [[Battle of Stones River|Murfreesboro]], [[Battle of Gettysburg|Gettysburg]] and [[Siege of Vicksburg|Vicksburg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/films/assassination/ |title=American Experience &#124; The Assassination of Abraham Lincoln |publisher=PBS |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>

==Preparations==
[[File:American Cousin Evening Star Apr 14 1865.png|thumb|left|Advertisement for ''Our American Cousin'' (Washington ''[[The Washington Star|Evening Star]]'', April 14, 1865)]]

On April 14, Booth's morning started at midnight. He wrote his mother that all was well, but that he was "in haste". In his diary, he wrote that "Our cause being almost lost, something ''decisive'' and great must be done".{{r|goodwin|p=728}}{{r|kunhardtlincoln|p=346}}

While visiting [[Ford's Theatre]] around noon to pick up his mail, Booth learned that Lincoln and Grant were to see ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' there that night. This provided him with an especially good opportunity to attack Lincoln since, having performed there several times, he knew the theater's layout and was familial to its staff.{{r|swanson|p=12}}{{r|steers|p=108–9}}
He went to Mary Surratt's boarding house in Washington, D.C. and asked her to deliver a package to her tavern in Surrattsville, Maryland. He also asked her to tell her tenant [[Louis J. Weichmann]] to ready the guns and ammunition that Booth had previously stored at the tavern.{{r|swanson|p=19}}

[[File:Fords Theatre.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Ford's Theatre]]

The conspirators met for the final time at 7{{nbsp}}p.m. Booth assigned [[Lewis Powell (assassin)|Lewis Powell]] to kill [[Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] at his home, [[George Atzerodt]] to kill [[Vice President]] [[Andrew Johnson]] at the Kirkwood Hotel, and [[David Herold|David E. Herold]] to guide Powell (who was unfamiliar with Washington) to the Seward house and then to a rendezvous with Booth in Maryland. Booth planned to shoot Lincoln with his single-shot [[Deringer]], and then stab Grant, at [[Ford's Theatre]]. They were all to strike simultaneously shortly after ten o'clock.{{r|steers|p=112}} Atzerodt tried to withdraw from the plot, which to this point had involved only kidnapping, not murder, but Booth pressured him to continue.{{r|kauffman|p=212}}

==Assassination of Lincoln==

[[File:This is the private box in Ford's Theater, Washington, where President Lincoln was assassinated by John Wilkes Booth, on - NARA - 559275.tif|thumb|left|Lincoln's box]]

===Lincoln arrives at the theater===

Despite what Booth had heard earlier in the day, Grant and his wife, [[Julia Grant]], had declined to accompany the Lincolns, as Mary Lincoln and Julia Grant were not on good terms.{{r|vowell|p=45}}{{efn|
There is evidence to suggest that either Booth or fellow conspirator [[Michael O'Laughlen]]{{snd}}who resembled Booth{{snd}}followed the Grants to [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]] late that afternoon and discovered that they would not be at the theater. The Grants later received an anonymous letter from someone who claimed to have boarded their train intending to attack them, but was thwarted because the Grants' private car was locked and guarded.<ref>McFeely (2002), ''Grant: A Biography'', pages 224–225</ref>}}
Others in succession also declined the Lincolns' invitation, until finally [[Major Henry Rathbone]] and his fiancée [[Clara Harris]] (daughter of [[New York State|New York]] Senator [[Ira Harris]]) accepted.{{r|swanson|p=32}}
At one point Mary Lincoln developed a headache and was inclined to stay home, but Lincoln told her he must attend because newspapers had announced that he would.<ref>{{cite book|last=Donald | first=David Herbert | title=Lincoln | location=New York | publisher=Touchstone | year=1995 | page=593}}</ref><!--THESE TWO ACCOUNTS CONFLICT, SO MAYBE SOMEONE ABOVE MY PAYGRADE CAN FIGURE OUT WHAT'S GOING ON-->
Lincoln's bodyguard, [[William H. Crook]], advised him not to go, but Lincoln said he had promised his wife.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Assassination of Lincoln: History and Myth|author=Lloyd Lewis|page=297|isbn=978-0-8032-7949-0|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|year=1994|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F6HB7q8M9TIC&pg=PA297}}</ref>
Lincoln told [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[Schuyler Colfax]], "I suppose it's time to go though I would rather stay" before assisting Mary into the carriage.

The presidential party arrived late and settled into their box, which was actually two boxes with a dividing partition removed. The play was interrupted and the orchestra played "[[Hail to the Chief]]" as the full house of some 1,700 rose in applause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/foth/faqs.htm |title=Frequently Asked Questions – Ford's Theatre National Historic Site |publisher=Nps.gov |date=February 12, 1932 |accessdate=September 28, 2012}}</ref>
Lincoln sat in a rocking chair which had been selected especially for him from among the Ford family's personal furnishings.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sneller|first1=Rhoda|last2=Sneller, Ph.D.|first2=Lowell|title=Lincoln Assassination Rocking Chair|url=http://www.abrahamlincolnonline.org/lincoln/education/arocker.htm|accessdate=August 26, 2017|quote=Theatre employee Joe Simms concurred{{nbsp}}... saying, 'I saw Mr. Harry Ford and another gentleman fixing up the box. Mr. Ford told me to go to his bed-room and get a rocking chair, and bring it down and put it in the President's box{{nbsp}}...'  James L. Maddox, another theatre worker, remembered Simms carrying the rocker into the building on his head. 'I had not seen that chair in the box this season; the last time I saw it before that afternoon was in the winter of 1863, when it was used by the President on his first visit to the theater.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Curating & Preserving The Lincoln Rocker|url=https://www.thehenryford.org/explore/inside/lincoln-rocker/|publisher=[[The Henry Ford|The Henry Ford Museum]]|accessdate=August 26, 2017}}</ref>

[[File:Gun used to assassinate Abraham Lincoln on display at Ford's Theatre, Washington, D.C.jpg|thumb|Booth's [[Philadelphia Deringer]] ]]

The cast modified a line of the play in honor of Lincoln: when the heroine asked for a seat protected from the draft, the reply{{snd}}scripted as, "Well, you're not the only one that wants to escape the [[conscription|draft]]"{{snd}}was delivered instead as, "The draft has already been stopped by order of the President!"<ref>{{cite book|last=Donald | first=David Herbert | title=Lincoln | location=New York | publisher=Touchstone | year=1995 | page=595}}</ref>
A member of the audience observed that Mary Lincoln often called her husband's attention to aspects of the action onstage, and "seemed to take great pleasure in witnessing his enjoyment."<ref>''The Darkest Dawn: Lincoln, Booth, and the Great American Tragedy.'' pg.88</ref>

At one point Mary Lincoln whispered to Lincoln, who was holding her hand, "What will Miss Harris think of my hanging on to you so?" Lincoln replied, "She won't think anything about it".{{r|swanson|p=39}} In following years these words were traditionally considered Lincoln's last, though N.W. Miner, a family friend, claimed in 1882 that Mary Lincoln told him that Lincoln's last words expressed a wish to visit [[Jerusalem]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miner|first1=Noyes W.|title=Personal Reminiscences of Abraham Lincoln|url=http://alplm-cdi.com/chroniclingillinois/items/show/15090|website=Chronicling Illinois|publisher=Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum|accessdate=August 27, 2017|date=July 10, 1882|quote=He said we will visit the Holy Land, and see those places hallowed by the footsteps of the Saviour. He was saying there was no city on earth he so much desired to see as Jerusalem}}</ref>

===Booth shoots Lincoln===

[[File:Assassination of President Lincoln.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|left|This [[Currier & Ives]] print (1865) implies Rathbone was already rising as Booth fired; in fact, Rathbone was unaware of Booth until he heard the shot.]]

Policeman [[John Frederick Parker]] was assigned to guard the president's box,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mrlincolnswhitehouse.org/inside.asp?ID=63&subjectID=2 |title=entry on John Parker at Mr. Lincoln's White House website |publisher=Mrlincolnswhitehouse.org |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> but at intermission he went to a nearby tavern along with Lincoln's footman and coachman. It is unclear whether he returned to the theater, but he was certainly not at his post when Booth entered the box.<ref>[http://rogerjnorton.com/Lincoln61.html John F. Parker: The Guard Who Abandoned His Post] at the Abraham Lincoln's Assassination website</ref> In any event, there is no certainty that entry would have been denied to a celebrity such as Booth, and the fact that Booth had prepared a brace to bar the door after entering the box would indicate he was expecting a guard to be present. Navy Surgeon George Brainerd Todd saw Booth arrive:<ref name = "Dr Todd">{{cite web|title=Dr. George Brainerd Todd Letter|url=http://www.bjpeters.com/bj/documents/FordsTheaterLetter.htm|publisher=Sauerbraten, Tea Time & Scones (B.J. Peters)|accessdate=August 7, 2012|author=Dr. George Brainerd Todd|date=April 14, 1865}}</ref>

{{quote|About 10:25 P.M., a man came in and walked slowly along the side on which the "Pres" box was and I heard a man say, "There's Booth" and I turned my head to look at him. He was still walking very slow and was near the box door when he stopped, took a card from his pocket, wrote something on it, and gave it to the usher who took it to the box. In a minute the door was opened and he walked in.}}

Once through this door, which swung inward, Booth barricaded it by wedging a stick between it and the wall. From here a second door led to Lincoln's box. There is evidence that, earlier in the day, Booth had bored a peephole in this second door, though this is not certain.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Dave|title=Thoughts From Major Rathbone|url=https://boothiebarn.com/2012/06/10/thoughts-from-major-rathbone/|website=BoothieBarn|accessdate=December 16, 2017|date=June 10, 2012}}</ref><ref name=bishop />{{rp|173}}

[[File:Police Blotter Listing the Assassination of President Lincoln - NARA - 301678.tif|thumb|upright=1.4|{{shy|Washington Metropolitan Police De|part|ment blotter for April 14 (lower quarter of page): "At this hour the mel|an|choly intel|li|gence of the assas|si|na|tion}} of Mr. Lincoln{{nbsp}}... was brought to this office{{nbsp}}... the assassin is a man named J. Wilks{{sic|nolink=yes}} Booth."]]

Booth knew the play by heart, and waited to time his shot with the laughter at one of the best lines of the play, delivered by actor [[Harry Hawk]]: "Well, I guess I know enough to turn you inside out, old gal; you [[wikt:sockdologizing|sockdologizing]] old man-trap!". Lincoln was laughing at this line when he was shot.<ref name=goodrich>{{cite book |title=The Darkest Dawn: Lincoln, Booth, and the Great American Tragedy |last=Goodrich |first=Thomas |publisher=Indiana University Press |date=2006 |isbn=9780253218896}}</ref>{{rp|96}}

Booth opened the door, stepped forward, and shot Lincoln from behind with a [[derringer#Phildelphia derringer|derringer]].{{r|Abel}} The bullet entered Lincoln's skull behind his left ear, passed through his brain, and came to rest near the front of the skull after fracturing both [[Orbital part of frontal bone|orbital plates]].{{efn|Though the steel ball Booth used as a bullet was of a .41 caliber, the derringer type was a small, easily concealable gun known to be inaccurate and usually just used in close quarters.,<ref name="Abel4">{{cite book|last1=Abel|first1=E. Lawrence|title=A Finger in Lincoln's Brain: What Modern Science Reveals about Lincoln, His Assassination, and Its Aftermath|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|at= Chapter 4}}</ref> The bullet most probably passed mainly through the left side of the brain causing massive damage including the skull fractures, hemorrhaging, and secondary severe edema (or swelling of the brain that occurred after the initial injury).  While Dr. Leale's notes mention Lincoln's bulging right eye,<ref name="Notes"/> the autopsy only specifically states the damage to the left side of the brain.<ref name= "Mackowiak"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=The autopsy of President Abraham Lincoln|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/visibleproofs/galleries/cases/lincoln.html|publisher=[[United States National Library of Medicine]]|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>}}<ref name= "Mackowiak">{{cite web|last1=Mackowiak|first1=Phillip|title=Would Lincoln Have Survived If He Was Shot Today?|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/11/would-lincoln-have-survived-if-he-was-shot-today/281680/|publisher=[[The Atlantic (magazine)|The Atlantic]]|date=November 29, 2013}}</ref> Lincoln slumped over in his chair and then fell backward.<ref>{{cite web|title=NPS Historical Handbook: Ford's Theatre|url=https://www.nps.gov/parkhistory/online_books/hh/3b/hh3e.htm|website=nps.gov|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=August 26, 2017|date=2002|quote=The President slumped forward in his chair, and then backward, never to regain consciousness.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kaplan|first1=Debbie Abrams|title=President Lincoln's slaying 150 years ago recalled at Ford's Theatre|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-tr-d-lincoln-fords-theatre-20150412-story.html|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 10, 2015}}</ref> Rathbone turned to see Booth standing in gunsmoke less than four feet behind Lincoln; Booth shouted a word that Rathbone thought sounded like "Freedom!"<ref>{{cite web|title=President Lincoln is Shot, 1865|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/lincolnshot.htm|website=EyeWitnesstoHistory|publisher=Ibis Communications|accessdate=August 27, 2017|quote=while I was intently observing the proceedings upon the stage, with my back toward the door, I heard the discharge of a pistol behind me, and, looking round, saw through the smoke a man between the door and the President. The distance from the door to where the President sat was about four feet. At the same time I heard the man shout some word, which I thought was 'Freedom!'}}</ref>

===Booth escapes===

[[File:John Wilkes Booth dagger.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.45|Booth's dagger]]

Rathbone jumped from his seat and struggled with Booth, who dropped the pistol and drew a knife, then stabbed Rathbone in the left forearm. Rathbone again grabbed at Booth as Booth prepared to jump from the box to the stage, a twelve-foot drop;<ref name="ReferenceA">''Lincoln Assassination'', History Channel</ref> Booth's [[spur|riding spur]] became entangled on the [[Lincoln assassination flags|Treasury flag decorating the box]], and he landed awkwardly on his left foot. As he began crossing the stage, many in the audience thought he was part of the play.

Booth held his bloody knife over his head, and yelled something to the audience.
While it is traditionally held that Booth shouted the [[Virginia]] state motto, ''[[Sic semper tyrannis]]!'' ("Thus always to tyrants") either from the box or from the stage, witness accounts conflict.{{r|goodwin|p=739}} Most recalled hearing ''Sic semper tyrannis!'' but others{{snd}}including Booth himself{{snd}}said he yelled only ''Sic semper!''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Booth|first1=John Wilkes|title=John Wilkes Booth's Diary|url=http://rogerjnorton.com/Lincoln52.html|publisher=Roger J. Norton|accessdate=December 16, 2017|date=April 1865}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/browser/1865/04/15/P1 | work=The New York Times | title=TimesMachine April 15, 1865 – New York Times}}</ref> (Some did not recall Booth saying anything in Latin.) There is similar uncertainty about what Booth shouted, next, in English: either "The South is avenged!",{{r|swanson|p=48}} "Revenge for the South!", or "The South shall be free!" (Two witnesses remembered Booth's words as: "I have done it!")

Immediately after Booth landed on the stage, Major Joseph B. Stewart climbed over the orchestra pit and footlights, and pursued Booth across the stage.{{r|ReferenceA}} The screams of Mary Lincoln and Clara Harris, and Rathbone's cries of "Stop that man!"{{r|swanson|p=49}} prompted others to join the chase as pandemonium broke out.

Booth ran across the stage and exited through a side door, en route stabbing orchestra leader William Withers, Jr.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bleyer |first=Bill |title=1906 Letter Tells What Five In Family Saw At Theatre April 14, 1865 |url=http://www.civilwarnews.com/archive/articles/2012/june/fordstheatre-061201.htm |work=Civil War News |publisher=Historical Publications Inc (Kathryn Jorgensen) |accessdate=May 2, 2014 |date=June 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502214633/http://www.civilwarnews.com/archive/articles/2012/june/fordstheatre-061201.htm |archivedate=May 2, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref name = "One Hundred">{{cite book|title=We Saw Lincoln Shot: One Hundred Eyewitness Accounts (quoting Katherine M. Evans interview from April 1915 ''[[New York Tribune]]'')|date=1995|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|pages=148–149|editor=Timothy S. Good}}</ref>
Booth had left a horse waiting outside in the alleyway.  As he leapt into the saddle Booth pushed Joseph Burroughs{{efn| Burroughs was also known as "John Peanut", "Peanut John", John Bohran, and other aliases.<ref name= "Evidence"/>}} (the man holding the horse) away, striking Burroughs with the handle of his knife.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lincoln's Last Day |url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/3b/hh3d.htm |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=May 2, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111209115459/http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/3b/hh3d.htm |archivedate=December 9, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lincoln's Last Day – Assassination and Death |url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/3b/hh3e.htm |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=May 2, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502214217/http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/3b/hh3e.htm |archivedate=May 2, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref name = "One Hundred John Miles">{{cite book|title=We Saw Lincoln Shot: One Hundred Eyewitness Accounts (quoting John Miles from Lincoln Conspiracy Trial transcripts)|date=1995|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|page=81|editor=Timothy S. Good}}</ref><ref name= "Evidence">{{cite book|editor1-last=Edwards|editor1-first=William C.|editor2-last=Steers|editor2-first=Edward|title=John Bohran (Joseph Burroughs) - The Lincoln Assassination: The Evidence|date=2010|publisher=University of Illinois Press|pages=140–141|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GvYpUeuPPrAC&pg=PA141#v=onepage&q&f=false|quote=He came up to the horse and put one foot in the stirrup and struck me with the butt of his dagger and knocked me down.}}</ref>

===Death of Lincoln===

[[File:Charles Leale - Brady-Handy.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.7|Surgeon [[Charles Leale]]]]

[[Charles Leale]], a young Army surgeon, pushed through the crowd to the door of Lincoln's box but found it would not open. Rathbone, inside the door, soon noticed and removed the wooden brace with which Booth had jammed it shut.{{r|steers|p=120}}

Leale entered the box to find Lincoln seated with his head leaning to his right<ref name="Notes">{{cite web|last1=Leale|first1=Charles A.|title=Report of Dr. Charles A. Leale on Assassination, April 15, 1865 (Page 5)|url=http://www.papersofabrahamlincoln.org/images/newdocuments/LealeReport5.jpg|website=papersofabrahamlincoln.org|publisher=The Papers of Abraham Lincoln, Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library|quote=Mr. Lincoln was seated in a high backed arm chair with his head leaning towards his right side supported by Mrs. Lincoln}}</ref> as Mary held him and sobbed: "His eyes were closed and he was in a profoundly comatose condition, while his breathing was intermittent and exceedingly [[stertor]]ous."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leale|first1=Charles A.|title=Report of Dr. Charles A. Leale on Assassination, April 15, 1865 (Page 6)|url=http://www.papersofabrahamlincoln.org/images/newdocuments/LealeReport6.jpg|website=papersofabrahamlincoln.org|publisher=The Papers of Abraham Lincoln, Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library|accessdate=August 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/report-first-doctor-reach-shot-lincoln-found-175353998.html|title=Report of first doctor to reach shot Lincoln found|author=John O'Connor|publisher=Associated Press|date=June 5, 2012|accessdate=August 26, 2017}}</ref> Thinking Lincoln had been stabbed, Leale shifted him to the floor. Meanwhile, another physician, [[Charles Sabin Taft]], was lifted from the stage into the box.

After Taft and Leale opened Lincoln's shirt and found no stab wound, Leale located the gunshot wound behind the left ear. He found the bullet too deep to be removed, but was able to dislodge a clot, after which Lincoln's breathing improved;{{r|steers|p=121-2}} he learned that regularly removing new clots maintained Lincoln's breathing. As actress [[Laura Keene]] cradled the President's head in her lap, he pronounced the wound mortal.{{r|swanson|p=78}}

[[File:Lincoln skull fragments and probe.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Skull fragments and probe used.]]

Leale, Taft, and another doctor, [[Albert Freeman Africanus King|Albert King]], decided that while Lincoln must be moved, a carriage ride to the [[White House]] was too dangerous. After considering [[Peter Taltavull]]'s Star Saloon next door, they concluded to take Lincoln to one of the houses across the way. It rained as soldiers carried Lincoln into the street,<ref name=Illinois2014>{{cite news | last = Blower | first = Janis | title = Geordie carried the dying U.S. president | newspaper = South Shields Gazette | location = England| publisher = shieldsgazette.com | date = March 14, 2013 | url = http://www.shieldsgazette.com/cookson-country/geordie-carried-the-dying-u-s-president-1-5499900 | accessdate = October 26, 2014}}</ref>
where a man urged them toward the [[Petersen House|house of tailor William Petersen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rogerjnorton.com/Lincoln7.html |title=Henry Safford |publisher=rogerjnorton.com |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601201201/http://rogerjnorton.com/Lincoln7.html| archivedate=June 1, 2011}}</ref> In Petersen's first-floor bedroom, the exceptionally tall Lincoln was laid diagonally on the bed.{{r|steers|p=123-4}}

[[File:Abraham Lincoln Deathbed.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.3|Lincoln's deathbed{{efn
|Julius Ulke, who was a boarder at the [[Petersen House]], took this photograph shortly after the President’s body was removed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert King Stone - Assassination of President Abraham Lincoln, 1865|url=https://www.archives.gov/exhibits/eyewitness/html.php?section=13|website=Eyewitness—American Originals from the National Archives|publisher=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|accessdate=September 8, 2017}}</ref>
}} ]]

More physicians arrived: [[Surgeon General of the United States Army|Surgeon General]] [[Joseph K. Barnes]], [[Charles Henry Crane]], [[Anderson Ruffin Abbott]], and [[Robert K. Stone]] (Lincoln's personal physician). All agreed Lincoln could not survive. Barnes probed the wound, locating the bullet and some bone fragments. Throughout the night, as the hemorrhage continued, they removed blood clots to relieve pressure on the brain,<ref name=donald>{{cite book|last=Donald | first=David Herbert | title=Lincoln | location=New York | publisher=Touchstone | year=1995 | page=594}}</ref>
and Leale held the comatose president's hand with a firm grip, "to let him know that he was in touch with humanity and had a friend."{{r|steers|page=14}}<ref name=bishopfriend>Jim Bishop, "Abe Lincoln's Last Friend," Reb Acres, December 27, 1977, September 27, 2009 [http://www.rebacres.com/index.php?page=15&article=17&hide=1 Abe Lincoln's Last Friend] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129101645/http://rebacres.com/index.php?page=15&article=17&hide=1 |date=2009-01-29 }}</ref>

Lincoln's older son [[Robert Todd Lincoln]] arrived sometime after midnight but twelve-year-old [[Tad Lincoln]] was kept away.
[[United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary of the Navy]] [[Gideon Welles]] and [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Edwin M. Stanton]] arrived. Stanton insisted that the sobbing Mary Lincoln leave the sick room, then for the rest of the night essentially ran the United States government from the house, including directing the hunt for Booth and his confederates.{{r|steers|p=127-8}}
Guards kept the public away, but numerous officials and physicians were admitted to pay their respects.{{r|donald}}

[[File:The Last Hours of Abraham Lincoln by Alonzo Chappel, 1868.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.8|''The Last Hours of Abraham Lincoln'' ([[Alonzo Chappel]], 1868){{efn
|Designed by John B. Bachelder, this painting depicts the various people who visited Lincoln's room at different times throughout the night as he lay dying; they were not all present simultaneously.
}} ]]

Initially, Lincoln's features were calm and his breathing slow and steady. Later one of his eyes became swollen and the right side of his face discolored.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of President Lincoln, 1865|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/lincoln.htm|website=EyeWitness to History|publisher=Ibis Communications, Inc.|accessdate=August 26, 2017|quote=His slow, full respiration lifted the clothes with each breath that he took. His features were calm and striking. I had never seen them appear to better advantage than for the first hour, perhaps, that I was there. After that his right eye began to swell and that part of his face became discolored.}}</ref> [[Maunsell Bradhurst Field]] wrote in a letter to ''[[The New York Times]]'' that the President then started "breathing regularly, but with effort, and did not seem to be struggling or suffering."<ref name="Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History">{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Richard|title=Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History|date=2015|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0393247244}}</ref><ref name = "OUR GREAT LOSS">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1865/04/17/news/our-great-loss-assassination-president-lincolndetails-fearful-crimeclosing.html|title=OUR GREAT LOSS; The Assassination of President Lincoln.DETAILS OF THE FEARFUL CRIME.Closing Moments and Death of the President.Probable Recovery of Secretary Seward. Rumors of the Arrest of the Assassins.The Funeral of President Lincoln to Take Place Next Wednesday.Expressions of Deep Sorrow Through-out the Land. OFFICIAL DISPATCHES. THE ASSASSINATION. Further Details of the Murder Narrow Recape of Secretary Stanton Measures Taken is Prevent the Escape of the Assassin of the President. LAST MOMENTS OF THE PRESIDENT. Interesting Letter from Maunsell B. Field Esq. THE GREAT CALAMITY.|date=April 17, 1865|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> As he neared death, Lincoln's appearance became "perfectly natural" <ref name="Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History"/> (except for the discoloration around his eyes).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Canavan|first1=Kathryn|title=Lincoln's Final Hours: Conspiracy, Terror, and the Assassination of America's Greatest President|date=2015|publisher=[[University of Kentucky Press]]|page=145|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cat3CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT145#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
Shortly before 7{{nbsp}}a.m. Mary was allowed to return to Lincoln's side,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of President Lincoln, 1865|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/lincoln.htm|website=EyeWitness to History|publisher=Ibis Communications, Inc.|accessdate=August 26, 2017}}</ref> and, as Dixon reported, "she again seated herself by the President, kissing him and calling him every endearing name."<ref>{{cite book|last=Donald | first=David Herbert | title=Lincoln | location=New York | publisher=Touchstone | year=1995 | page=599}}</ref>

Lincoln died at 7:22&nbsp;a.m. on April 15.{{R|Heritage}}
Mary Lincoln was not present.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bain|first1=Robert T.|title=Lincoln's Last Battleground: A Tragic Night Recalled|date=2005|publisher=AuthorHouse|page=6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D4uhpzL9TT0C&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Emerson|first1=Jason|title=Mary Lincoln's Insanity Case: A Documentary History|date=2012|publisher=University of Illinois Press|page=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pqvzAgCDHF4C&pg=PA3#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In his last moments Lincoln's face became calm and his breathing quieter.<ref>{{cite book |author=Tarbell, Ida Minerva |title=The Life of Abraham Lincoln |volume=4 |pages=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TDhpaY4aHYC&pg=RA1-PA34#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher= |date= |accessdate= |year=1920 }}</ref> Field wrote there was "no apparent suffering, no convulsive action, no rattling of the throat ... [only] a mere cessation of breathing".<ref name="Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History">{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Richard|title=Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History|date=2015|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0393247244}}</ref><ref name = "OUR GREAT LOSS"/>
According to Lincoln's secretary [[John Hay]], at the moment of Lincoln's death, "a look of unspeakable peace came upon his worn features".<ref>{{cite book|last=Hay|first=John|title=The Life and Letters of John Hay Volume 1 (quote's original source is Hay's diary which is quoted in "Abraham Lincoln: A History", Volume 10, Page 292 by John G. Nicolay and John Hay)|date=1915|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company|url=https://archive.org/stream/lifeandlettersof007751mbp/lifeandlettersof007751mbp_djvu.txt}}</ref>
The assembly knelt for a prayer, after which Stanton said either "Now he belongs to the ages" or "Now he belongs to the angels."{{r|steers|p=134}}<ref name=Townsend>{{cite book|author=Townsend, George Alfred|title=The Life, Crime and Capture of John Wilkes Booth|location=New York|publisher=[[Dick and Fitzgerald]]|year=1865}}</ref>

On Lincoln's death, Vice President Johnson became president, and was sworn in by Chief Justice [[Salmon Chase]] between 10 and 11{{nbsp}}a.m.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Trefousse|first1=Hans L.|title=Andrew Johnson: A Biography|date=1989|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company.|page=194}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Powell attacks Seward==
[[File:FSewardLPaine.jpg|thumb|left|An artist's depiction of [[Lewis Powell (assassin)|Lewis Powell]] attacking [[William Seward]]'s son,
 [[Frederick W. Seward]] ]]

Booth had assigned Lewis Powell to kill [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]]. On April 5 Seward had been thrown from his carriage, suffering a concussion, a broken jaw, and a broken arm. On the night of the assassination he was confined to bed at his home in [[President's Park|Lafayette Park]]. Herold guided Powell to Seward's house. Powell carried an 1858 Whitney revolver (a large, heavy and popular gun during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]) and a [[Bowie knife]].

[[William H. Bell (fl. 1860s)|William Bell]], Seward's butler, answered the door when Powell knocked slightly after 10&nbsp;p.m. Powell told Bell that he had medicine from Seward's physician, and that his instructions were to personally show Seward how to take it. Overcoming Bell's skepticism, Powell made his way up the stairs to Seward's third-floor bedroom.{{r|swanson|p=54}}{{r|goodwin|p=736}}<ref name="TownsendLifeBooth">George Alfred Townsend, ''The Life, Crime and Capture of John Wilkes Booth''. ({{ISBN|978-0-9764805-3-2}})</ref> At the top of the staircase he was stopped by Seward's son, [[United States Assistant Secretary of State|Assistant Secretary of State]] [[Frederick W. Seward]], to whom he repeated the medicine story; Frederick, suspicious, said his father was asleep.

[[File:William Seward and Daughter Fanny.png|right|upright=1|thumb|William and Fanny Seward in 1861]]

Hearing voices, Seward's daughter [[Frances Adeline "Fanny" Seward|Fanny]] emerged from Seward's room and said, "Fred, Father is awake now"{{snd}}thus revealing to Powell where Seward was. Powell turned as if to start downstairs, but suddenly turned again and drew his revolver. He aimed at Frederick's forehead and pulled the trigger, but the gun misfired so he bludgeoned Frederick unconscious with it. Bell, yelling "Murder! Murder!", ran outside for help.

Fanny opened the door again and Powell shoved past her to Seward's bed. He stabbed at Seward's face and neck, slicing open his cheek,{{r|swanson|p=58}} but the splint doctors had fitted to Seward's broken jaw (often mistakenly described as a [[neck brace]]) prevented the blade from penetrating his [[jugular]] vein.{{r|goodwin|p=737}} He eventually recovered, though with serious scars on his face.

Seward's son [[Augustus Henry Seward|Augustus]] and Sergeant [[George F. Robinson]], a soldier assigned to Seward, were alerted by Fanny's screams and received stab wounds in struggling with Powell.
As Augustus went for a pistol, Powell ran downstairs toward the door,{{r|sandburg|p=275}} where he encountered Emerick Hansell, a State Department messenger.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Swain|first1=Claudia|title=Even More Little Known Victims of the Lincoln Assassination Plot|url=https://blogs.weta.org/boundarystones/2013/03/28/even-more-little-known-victims-lincoln-assassination-plot|publisher=WETA|accessdate=December 16, 2017|date=March 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Dave|title=Emerick Hansell: The Forgotten Casualty|url=https://boothiebarn.com/2015/09/04/emerick-hansell-the-forgotten-casualty/#_edn11|website=BoothieBarn|accessdate=December 16, 2017|date=September 4, 2015}}</ref>  Powell stabbed Hansell in the back, then ran outside exclaiming "I'm mad! I'm mad!". Screams from the house had frightened Herold, who ran off, leaving Powell to find his own way in an unfamiliar city.{{r|swanson|p=59}}

==Atzerodt fails to attack Johnson==
[[File:George Atzerodt2.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.75|George Atzerodt]]
[[File:Andrew Johnson by Vannerson, 1859.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.70|Andrew Johnson]]

Booth had assigned [[George Atzerodt]] to kill Vice President [[Andrew Johnson]], who was staying at the Kirkwood House in Washington. Atzerodt was to go to Johnson's room at 10:15&nbsp;p.m. and shoot him.{{r|goodwin|p=735}} On April 14 Atzerodt rented the room directly above Johnson's; the next day he arrived there at the appointed time and, carrying a gun and knife, went to the bar downstairs, where he asked the bartender about Johnson's character and behavior.  He eventually became drunk and wandered off through the streets, tossing his knife away at some point. He made his way to the Pennsylvania House Hotel by 2 a.m., where he obtained a room and went to sleep.{{r|steers|p=166-7}}{{r|sandburg|p=335}}

Earlier in the day, Booth had stopped by the Kirkwood House and left a note for Johnson: "I don't wish to disturb you. Are you at home? J. Wilkes Booth."{{R|TownsendLifeBooth}} One theory holds that Booth was trying to find out whether Johnson was expected at the Kirkwood that night;{{r|steers|p=111}} another holds that Booth, concerned that Atzerodt would fail to kill Johnson, intended the note to implicate Johnson in the conspiracy.<ref>U.S. Senate: Art & History Home. "[https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/generic/VP_Andrew_Johnson.htm Andrew Johnson, 16th Vice President (1865)]", United States Senate. Retrieved February 17, 2006.</ref>{{clear left}}

==Reactions==
{{Further|Funeral and burial of Abraham Lincoln}}
[[File:LincolnTrain.jpeg|thumb|upright=1|left|Lincoln's funeral train]]

Lincoln was mourned in both the North and South,{{r|sandburg|p=350}}
and indeed around the world.<ref name="Atlantic">{{cite web|last=Ford|first=Matt|title=How the World Mourned Lincoln|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/04/how-the-world-mourned-lincoln/390465/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=April 14, 2015}}</ref> Numerous foreign governments issued proclamations and declared periods of mourning on April 15.{{R|NPR}}<ref name="Historian">{{cite web|last=Marrs|first=Aaron|title=INTERNATIONAL REACTION TO LINCOLN'S DEATH|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus-history/research/international-reaction-to-lincoln|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]], [[Office of the Historian]]|date=December 12, 2011|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>
Lincoln was praised in sermons on [[Easter Sunday]], which fell on the day after his death.{{r|sandburg|p=357}}

On April 18, mourners lined up seven abreast for a mile to view Lincoln in his walnut casket in the White House's black-draped [[East Room]]. Special trains brought thousands from other cities, some of whom slept on the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]]'s lawn.{{r|kunhardttwenty|p=120-123}} Hundreds of thousands watched the funeral procession on April 19,{{r|swanson|p=213}} and millions more lined the {{convert|1700|mi|km|adj=on}} route of the train which took Lincoln's remains through New York to [[Springfield, Illinois]], often passing trackside tributes in the form of bands, bonfires, and hymn-singing.<ref name="trostel">{{cite book|last1=Trostel|first1=Scott D.|title=The Lincoln funeral train: the final journey and national funeral for Abraham Lincoln|date=2002|publisher=Cam-Tech Pub.|location=Fletcher, Ohio|isbn=978-0925436214}}</ref>{{rp|31–58}}{{r|goodrich|pp=231–238}}

[[File:TheApotheosisLincolnAndWashington1860s.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.65|Lincoln ascending to heaven, where [[George Washington]] crowns him with laurels. Unknown artist. ]]

Poet [[Walt Whitman]] composed "[[When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd]]", "[[O Captain! My Captain!]]", and two other poems, to eulogize Lincoln.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=The Walt Whitman Archive – Published Works: O Captain! My Captain!|url=http://whitmanarchive.org/published/periodical/poems/per.00076|website=www.whitmanarchive.org|publisher=[[University of Nebraska–Lincoln#Digital Research|Center for Digital Research (University of Nebraska-Lincoln)]]|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Peck | first=Garrett | title=Walt Whitman in Washington, D.C.: The Civil War and America's Great Poet | year=2015 | publisher=The History Press | location=Charleston, SC | isbn=978-1-62619-973-6 | pages=118–23}}</ref>

Ulysses S. Grant called Lincoln "incontestably the greatest man I ever knew."{{r|goodwin|p=747}} [[Robert E. Lee]] expressed sadness.<ref name=kunhardtsmithsonian>Kunhardt III, Philip B., "Lincoln's Contested Legacy," ''Smithsonian'', pp. 34–35.</ref> Southern-born [[Elizabeth Blair Lee|Elizabeth Blair]] said that, "Those of Southern born sympathies know now they have lost a friend willing and more powerful to protect and serve them than they can now ever hope to find again."{{r|goodwin|p=744}}
African-American orator [[Frederick Douglass]] called the assassination an "unspeakable calamity".<ref name=kunhardtsmithsonian />

[[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|British Foreign Secretary]] [[John Russell, 1st Earl Russell|Lord Russell]] called Lincoln's death a "sad calamity."{{R|Historian}} [[Qing dynasty|China]]'s chief secretary of state for foreign affairs, [[Prince Kung]], described himself as "inexpressibly shocked and startled".<ref name="NPR">{{cite web|last=Northam|first=Jackie|title=Documents Show Global Outpouring Of Grief Over Lincoln's Assassination|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/04/15/399813809/documents-show-global-outpouring-of-grief-over-lincolns-assassination|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=April 15, 2015|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>
[[President of Ecuador|Ecuadorian President]] [[Gabriel Garcia Moreno]] said, "Never should I have thought that the noble country of Washington would be humiliated by such a black and horrible crime; nor should I ever have thought that Mr. Lincoln would come to such a horrible end, after having served his country which such wisdom and glory under so critical circumstances."{{R|NPR}}{{R|Historian}}
The [[government of Liberia]] issued a proclamation calling Lincoln "not only the ruler of his own people, but a father to millions of a race stricken and oppressed."{{R|Historian}} The [[government of Haiti]] condemned the assassination as a "horrid crime."{{R|Historian}}

==Flight and capture of the conspirators==

[[File:Booth escape route.svg|thumb|left|upright=1.5|Booth's escape route]]

===Booth and Herold===

Within half an hour of fleeing Ford's Theatre, Booth crossed the Navy Yard Bridge into [[Maryland]].{{r|swanson|p=67–8}}  An army sentry questioned him about his late-night travel; Booth said that he was going home to the nearby town of Charles. Though it was forbidden for civilians to cross the bridge after 9 p.m., the sentry let him through.<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Reilly|first=Bill|title=[[Killing Lincoln]]|year=2011|publisher=Henry Holt & Company, LLC|page=215}}</ref> [[David Herold]] made it across the same bridge less than an hour later{{r|swanson|p=81-2}} and rendezvoused with Booth.{{r|swanson|p=87}} After retrieving weapons and supplies previously stored at [[Clinton, Maryland|Surattsville]], Herold and Booth went to the home of [[Samuel A. Mudd]], a local doctor, who splinted the leg Booth had broken in jumping from the presidential box, and later made a pair of crutches for Booth.{{r|swanson|p=131,153}}

After a day at Mudd's house, Booth and Herold hired a local man to guide them to [[Rich Hill (Bel Alton, Maryland)|Samuel Cox's house]].{{r|swanson|p=163}} Cox in turn took them to Thomas Jones, a Confederate sympathizer who hid Booth and Herold in [[Zekiah Swamp]] for five days until they could cross the [[Potomac River]].{{r|swanson|p=224}} On the afternoon of April 24, they arrived at the farm of Richard H. Garrett, a tobacco farmer, in [[King George County, Virginia]]. Booth told Garrett he was a wounded Confederate soldier.

[[File:John Wilkes Booth wanted poster.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|Reward broadside with photographs of [[John H. Surratt]], [[John Wilkes Booth]], and [[David E. Herold]] ]]

An April 15 letter to Todd from his brother tells of the rumors in Washington about Booth:

{{quote|Today all the city is in mourning nearly every house being in black and I have not seen a smile, no business, and many a strong man I have seen in tears{{snd}}Some reports say Booth is a prisoner, others that he has made his escape – but from orders received here, I believe he is taken, and during the night will be put on a [[Monitor (warship)#American Civil War|Monitor]] for safe keeping – as a mob once raised now would know no end.{{R|Dr Todd}} }}

The hunt for the conspirators quickly became the largest in U.S. history, involving thousands of federal troops and countless civilians. [[Edwin M. Stanton]] personally directed the operation,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Martelle|first1=Scott|title=The Madman and the Assassin: The Strange Life of Boston Corbett, the Man Who Killed John Wilkes Booth|date=2015|publisher=Chicago Review Press|page=87}}</ref> authorizing rewards of $50,000 ({{inflation|US|50,000|1865|fmt=eq|r=-5}}) for Booth and $25,000 each for Herold and John Surratt.<ref>{{cite web|title=$100,000 Reward!|url=http://www.civilwar.si.edu/lincoln_reward.html|website=CivilWar@Smithsonian|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref>

Booth and Herold were sleeping at Garrett's farm on April 26 when soldiers from the [[16th Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry|16th New York Cavalry]] arrived and surrounded the barn, then threatened to set fire to it. Herold surrendered, but Booth cried out, "I will not be taken alive!"{{r|swanson|p=326}} The soldiers set fire to the barn{{r|swanson|p=331}} and Booth scrambled for the back door with a rifle and pistol.

Sergeant [[Boston Corbett]] crept up behind the barn and shot Booth in "the back of the head about an inch below the spot where his [Booth's] shot had entered the head of Mr. Lincoln",<ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of John Wilkes Booth, 1865|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/booth.htm|publisher=Eyewitness to History/Ibis Communications|accessdate=August 16, 2012}} (Quoting Lieutenant Edward Doherty, officer in charge of the soldiers who captured Booth)</ref> severing his spinal cord.{{r|swanson|p=335}} Booth was carried out onto the steps of the barn. A soldier poured water into his mouth, which he spat out, unable to swallow. Booth told the soldier, "Tell my mother I die for my country." Unable to move his limbs, he asked a soldier to lift his hands before his face and whispered his last words as he gazed at them: "Useless&nbsp;... useless." He died on the porch of the Garrett farm two hours later.{{r|swanson|p=336-40}}{{R|TownsendLifeBooth}} Corbett was initially arrested for disobeying orders, but was later released and was largely considered a hero by the media and the public.{{r|goodrich|p=228}}

===Others===

[[File:Garrett Farm.gif|thumb|upright=1.2|left|The Garrett farmhouse, where Booth died April 26]]

Without Herold to guide him, Powell did not find his way back to the Surratt house until April 17. He told detectives waiting there that he was a ditch-digger hired by [[Mary Surratt]], but she denied knowing him. Both were arrested.{{r|steers|p=174-9}} [[George Atzerodt]] hid at his cousin's farm in [[Germantown, Maryland]], about {{convert|25|mi|km}} northwest of Washington, where he was arrested April 20.{{r|steers|p=169}}

The remaining conspirators were arrested by month's end{{snd}}except for [[John Surratt]], who fled to Quebec where he was hidden by Roman Catholic priests. In September, he boarded a ship to Liverpool, England, staying in the Catholic Church of the Holy Cross there. From there, he moved furtively through Europe until joining the [[Pontifical Zouaves]] in the [[Papal States]]. A friend from his school days recognized him in there in early 1866 and alerted the U.S. government. Surratt was arrested by the Papal authorities but managed to escape under suspicious circumstances. He was finally captured by an agent of the United States in Egypt in November 1866.{{R|harris}}{{clear left}}

==Conspirators' trial and execution==
[[File:Trial of conspirators in Lincoln's assassination CDV, 1865.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.5|Trial of the conspirators, June 5, 1865]]

Scores of persons were arrested, including many tangential associates of the conspirators and anyone having had even the slightest contact with Booth or Herold during their flight. These included [[Louis J. Weichmann]], a boarder in Mrs. Surratt's house; Booth's brother [[Junius Brutus Booth, Jr.|Junius]] (in Cincinnati at the time of the assassination); theater owner [[John T. Ford]]; [[James W. Pumphrey|James Pumphrey]], from whom Booth hired his horse; [[John M. Lloyd]], the innkeeper who rented Mrs. Surratt's Maryland tavern and gave Booth and Herold weapons and supplies the night of April 14; and Samuel Cox and Thomas A. Jones, who helped Booth and Herold cross the Potomac.{{r|kunhardttwenty|p=186-8}}
All were eventually released except:{{r|kunhardttwenty|p=188}}
{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|
* [[Samuel Arnold (Lincoln conspirator)|Samuel Arnold]]
* [[George Atzerodt]]
* [[David Herold]]
* [[Samuel Mudd]]
* [[Michael O'Laughlen]]
* [[Lewis Powell (assassin)|Lewis Powell]]
* [[Edmund Spangler]] (a theater stagehand who had given Booth's horse to Burroughs to hold)
* [[Mary Surratt]]
}}
The accused were tried by a [[military tribunal]] ordered by Johnson, who had succeeded to the presidency on Lincoln's death:
{{columns-list|colwidth=19em|
* [[Major general (United States)|Maj. Gen.]] [[David Hunter]] (presiding)
* Maj. Gen. [[Lew Wallace]]
* [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brig. Gen.]] [[Robert Sanford Foster]]
* Brig. Gen. [[Thomas Maley Harris]]
* Brig. Gen. [[Albion P. Howe]]
* Brig. Gen. [[August Kautz]]
* [[Colonel (United States)|Col.]] [[James A. Ekin]]
* Col. [[Charles H. Tompkins]]
* [[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lt. Col.]] [[David Ramsay Clendenin]]
}}
The prosecution was led by U.S. Army Judge Advocate General [[Joseph Holt]], assisted by [[United States Congress|Congressman]] [[John A. Bingham]] and [[Major (United States)|Major]] [[Henry Lawrence Burnett]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Doug Linder |url=http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/lincolnconspiracy/lincolnaccount.html |title=The Trial of the Lincoln Assassination Conspirators |publisher=Law.umkc.edu |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620053806/http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/lincolnconspiracy/lincolnaccount.html |archivedate=June 20, 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>

The use of a military tribunal provoked criticism from [[Edward Bates]] and [[Gideon Welles]], who believed that a civil court should have presided; but [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[James Speed]] pointed to the military nature of the conspiracy and the facts that the defendants acted as enemy combatants and that [[martial law]] was in force at the time in the [[District of Columbia]]. (In 1866, in ''[[Ex parte Milligan]]'', the [[United States Supreme Court]] banned the use of military tribunals in places where civil courts were operational.){{r|steers|p=213-4}} Only a simple majority of the jury was required for a guilty verdict, and a two-thirds for a death sentence. There was no route for appeal other than to President Johnson.{{r|steers|p=222-3}}

[[File:Execution Lincoln assassins.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.3|Execution of [[Mary Surratt]], [[Lewis Powell (assassin)|Lewis Powell]], [[David Herold]], and [[George Atzerodt]] on July 7, 1865, at [[Fort Lesley J. McNair|Fort McNair]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington City]]]]

The seven-week trial included the testimony of 366 witnesses. All of the defendants were found guilty on June 30. Mary Surratt, Lewis Powell, David Herold, and George Atzerodt were sentenced to death by [[hanging]]; Samuel Mudd, Samuel Arnold, and Michael O'Laughlen were sentenced to life in prison.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Steers|first1=Edward|title=Lincoln's Assassination|date=2014|publisher=SIU Press|page=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sSh9BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA116}}</ref> Edmund Spangler was sentenced to six years. After sentencing Mary Surratt to hang, five jurors signed a letter recommending clemency, but Johnson refused to stop the execution; he later claimed he never saw the letter.{{r|steers|p=227}}

Mary Surratt, Powell, Herold, and Atzerodt were hanged in the [[Fort Lesley J. McNair|Old Arsenal Penitentiary]] on July 7.{{r|swanson|p=362,365}} Mary Surratt was the first woman executed by the United States government.<ref>Linder, D: "[http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/lincolnconspiracy/surrattm.html Biography of Mary Surratt, Lincoln Assassination Conspirator] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224091138/http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/lincolnconspiracy/surrattm.html |date=2009-02-24 }}", University of Missouri–Kansas City. Retrieved December 10, 2006.</ref> O'Laughlen died in prison in 1867. Mudd, Arnold, and Spangler were pardoned in February 1869 by Johnson.{{r|swanson|p=367}} Spangler, who died in 1875, always insisted his sole connection to the plot was that Booth asked him to hold his horse.

John Surratt stood trial in Washington in 1867. Four residents of [[Elmira, New York]],{{r|swanson|p=27}}{{r|serup|p=125,132,136-7}}{{r|jampoler|p=112-5}} claimed they had seen him there between April 13 and 15; fifteen others said they either saw him, or someone who resembled him, in Washington (or traveling to or from Washington) on the day of the assassination. The jury could not reach a verdict and John Surratt was released.{{r|steers|p=178}}{{r|serup|p=132-3,138}}{{r|larson|p=227}}

